	abstract = {The emergence of wearable health sensors in the last decade has the potential to revolutionize the study of sleep and circadian rhythms. In particular, recent progress has been made in the use of mathematical models in the prediction of a patient’s internal circadian state using data measured by wearable devices. This is a vital step in our ability to identify optimal circadian timing for health interventions. We review the available data for fitting circadian phase models with a focus on wearable data sets. Finally, we review the current modeling paradigms and explore avenues for developing personalized parameter sets in limit cycle oscillator models to further improve prediction accuracy.},
